# leakfix

[![PyPI version](https://badge.fury.io/py/leakfix.svg)](https://badge.fury.io/py/leakfix)
[![License: MIT](https://img.shields.io/badge/License-MIT-yellow.svg)](https://opensource.org/licenses/MIT)

**One-stop CLI tool to detect, remove, and prevent secrets in git repositories.**

---

## The Problem

Accidental secret leaks in git repositories are common and costly. A typical scenario: a developer backs up `.env` as `.env.bak`, forgets to add it to `.gitignore`, and commits it—exposing API keys, tokens, and credentials. Once pushed, secrets live in history forever unless actively purged.

**leakfix** was built to solve this. It detects secrets (including in git history), removes them safely, and helps prevent future leaks.

---

## Features

- **Scan** — Working directory, staged files, or full git history
- **Fix** — Replace secrets in files or purge from history (via `git-filter-repo`)
- **Smart classification** — Distinguish real secrets from placeholders (e.g. `glpat-your-token`)
- **Pre-commit hook** — Block commits that contain secrets
- **Guard mode** — Watch for dangerous files (`.env.bak`, etc.) before they’re committed
- **Gitignore audit** — Ensure `.env*`, `.pem`, and similar patterns are ignored
- **Org scan** — Scan multiple repos (local dir, GitLab group, or GitHub org)
- **Reports** — HTML, JSON, CSV, PDF

---

## Installation

### pip

```bash
pip install leakfix
```

### Homebrew (macOS)

```bash
brew install leakfix
```

### Dependencies

leakfix requires these external tools for full functionality:

| Tool | Required for | Install |
|------|--------------|---------|
| [gitleaks](https://github.com/gitleaks/gitleaks) | Scan (all modes) | `brew install gitleaks` |
| [git-filter-repo](https://github.com/newren/git-filter-repo) | History rewrite (fix) | `brew install git-filter-repo` |

> **Homebrew caveats:** If you install leakfix via Homebrew, you must install gitleaks and git-filter-repo separately. They are not bundled with the leakfix formula.
> ```bash
> brew install gitleaks git-filter-repo
> ```

---

## Setup

Run the interactive setup wizard to verify dependencies and optionally enable LLM enhancement:

```bash
leakfix setup
```

| Option | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| (default) | Full setup wizard: dependency check + optional LLM |
| `--check` | Check dependencies only, no prompts |
| `--llm` | Jump straight to LLM setup only |
| `--reset` | Reset config and re-run full setup |

### LLM Enhancement

Leakfix can use a **local AI model** to improve false positive detection. When enabled:

- **What it does:** Uses Ollama to classify uncertain findings (REVIEW_NEEDED) as real secrets or placeholders.
- **How to enable:** Run `leakfix setup` and choose "Y" when prompted, or run `leakfix setup --llm`.
- **Model options:** `qwen3:0.6b` (fastest, 2GB RAM, recommended), `llama3.2:3b` (balanced, 4GB RAM), `phi4` (best quality, 10GB RAM).
- **Privacy:** 100% local — no data ever leaves your device. Requires [Ollama](https://ollama.ai) and `pip install ollama`.

If you use `--llm` without setup, leakfix will prompt you to run setup and optionally enable LLM.

---

## Quick Start

```bash
# Scan for secrets
leakfix scan

# Scan staged files (pre-commit style)
leakfix scan --staged

# Scan full history
leakfix scan --history

# Fix secrets in working files only
leakfix fix --files-only

# Fix and purge from history (rewrites commits)
leakfix fix --no-push

# Install pre-commit hook
leakfix install-hook

# Check .gitignore for missing patterns
leakfix gitignore --check
```

---

## All Commands

### `leakfix scan` [PATH]

Scan repository for leaked secrets.

| Option | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| (default) | Scan working directory |
| `--staged` | Scan only staged files (for pre-commit hook) |
| `--history` | Scan full git history |
| `--all` | Scan working dir + history |
| `--hook-mode` | Special output for hooks: mask secrets, check dangerous files |
| `--smart` | Classify findings (CONFIRMED vs FALSE_POSITIVE vs REVIEW_NEEDED) |
| `--llm` | Use LLM to classify REVIEW_NEEDED findings (requires ollama) |
| `-o, --output table\|json\|html` | Output format (default: table) |
| `-s, --severity high\|medium\|low` | Filter by severity |

### `leakfix fix` [PATH]

Fix/remove detected secrets in working files and git history.

| Option | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| `--files-only` | Only fix working files |
| `--history-only` | Only rewrite history |
| `--no-push` | Fix locally but don't force push |
| `--dry-run` | Show what would be replaced without making changes |
| `--replace-with TEXT` | Custom replacement string (default: empty) |
| `--confirm` | Ask for confirmation before each replacement |
| `--include-review` | Also fix REVIEW_NEEDED secrets |
| `--llm` | Use LLM to classify REVIEW_NEEDED findings (requires ollama) |

### `leakfix setup`

Interactive setup wizard.

| Option | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| (default) | Full setup: dependency check + optional LLM |
| `--check` | Just check dependencies, no prompts |
| `--llm` | Jump straight to LLM setup only |
| `--reset` | Reset config and re-run full setup |

### `leakfix classify` VALUE [OPTIONS]

Manually check if a value is likely a false positive.

| Option | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| `--file TEXT` | Optional file path for context (e.g. .env.example) |
| `--llm` | Use LLM to classify (requires ollama) |

```bash
leakfix classify "glpat-your-gitlab-personal-access-token"   # → LIKELY_FALSE_POSITIVE
leakfix classify "glpat-J5UZoBWeFCqCh6C5vwAN" --llm         # → CONFIRMED
```

### `leakfix install-hook` [PATH]

Install pre-commit hook to prevent secret leaks.

| Option | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| `--smart` | Use smart classification (skip likely false positives in hook) |

### `leakfix uninstall-hook` [PATH]

Remove the pre-commit hook.

### `leakfix hook-status` [PATH]

Check if pre-commit hook is installed and active.

### `leakfix scan-org`

Scan organization repositories for secrets.

| Option | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| `--path PATH` | Scan all git repos under this directory |
| `--gitlab TEXT` | GitLab base URL (use with --group) |
| `--github` | Scan GitHub org (use with --org) |
| `--token TEXT` | API token (or GITLAB_TOKEN / GITHUB_TOKEN env) |
| `--group TEXT` | GitLab group/namespace |
| `--org TEXT` | GitHub organization |
| `--fix` | Run leakfix fix on all affected repos after scan |
| `--report PATH` | Write unified HTML report |
| `--exclude TEXT` | Comma-separated repo names to exclude |
| `--parallel INT` | Number of parallel scans (default: 2) |
| `--no-push` | With --fix: fix locally but don't force push |
| `--smart` | Filter findings with classifier |

```bash
leakfix scan-org --path /path/to/repos
leakfix scan-org --path /path/to/repos --exclude repo1,repo2 --report report.html
leakfix scan-org --path /path/to/repos --fix --no-push --parallel 4
```

### `leakfix report` [PATH]

Generate report of detected secrets.

| Option | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| `-f, --format html\|pdf\|json\|csv` | Report format (default: html) |
| `-o, --output PATH` | Output file path |
| `--since TEXT` | Filter findings since date (YYYY-MM-DD) |
| `--author TEXT` | Filter by commit author (substring match) |
| `--smart` | Include classification breakdown |

### `leakfix guard` [OPTIONS] [COMMAND]

Run guard/watch mode to prevent leaks.

| Option | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| `--daemon` | Run as background daemon |
| `-p, --path PATH` | Repository path to watch (default: .) |

| Subcommand | Description |
|------------|-------------|
| `status` | Check if guard is running |
| `stop` | Stop the guard daemon |

```bash
leakfix guard                    # Foreground
leakfix guard --daemon           # Background
leakfix guard status             # Check status
leakfix guard stop               # Stop daemon
```

### `leakfix gitignore` [PATH]

Audit and fix `.gitignore` for secret-related patterns.

| Option | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| `--check` | Just check and report, don't modify |
| `--generate` | Generate a security-focused .gitignore from scratch |

```bash
leakfix gitignore                # Audit and add missing patterns
leakfix gitignore --check        # Only report missing patterns
leakfix gitignore --generate     # Generate new .gitignore
```

---

## Configuration

### `.leakfixignore`

Exclude paths from scanning (similar to `.gitignore`):

```
vendor/
node_modules/
*.min.js
```

### `.gitleaks.toml`

Place a `.gitleaks.toml` in your repo root to use custom detection rules. leakfix will respect it and skip its bundled extended config. See [gitleaks config](https://github.com/gitleaks/gitleaks#configuration).

---

## How It Works

1. **Detection** — Uses [gitleaks](https://github.com/gitleaks/gitleaks) with extended rules for JIRA (`ATATT...`), Figma (`figd_...`), and generic `sk-` API keys.
2. **Classification** — Entropy, placeholder patterns, and file context (e.g. `.env.example`) to reduce false positives.
3. **Fix** — Working files: in-place replacement. History: [git-filter-repo](https://github.com/newren/git-filter-repo) to rewrite commits and remove secrets.

